3. Reflection of teachers

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1. learn the on-site data-collection skills and techniques for fieldwork;
2. explore and develop his/her own research interests;
3. work in a team for an agreed goal/product and enhance the outcomes with the feedback received

4. present his/her own idea through verbal and written presentations

5. establish feasible plans to manage available resources for an agreed goal/product

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to:

1. state the key issues and concepts in the field of men’s and masculinities studies;

2. distinguish the competing theoretical approaches to men and masculinities;

3. understand men and masculinities in a cross-cultural perspective;

4. recognize that social class, sexuality, race/ethnicity and age cut across the issues pertinent to men’s and masculinities studies;

5. comment on the strengths and weaknesses of various theoretical approaches to men and masculinities;

6. theorize contemporary social issues in relation to men and masculinities;

7. critically engage with inequality in society in relation to different modes and notions of masculinities.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to

1. describe how minorities are historically, socially and economically constructed and their lived experiences;

2. understand and identify issues pertinent to multifarious minorities in Hong Kong with political economy, feminist, critical race theory phenomenological and queer approaches;

3. identify and analyse in what way power relations are established and resisted in the construction of minorities and the social as well as institutional responses to them in the form of public policy.

4. increase awareness of SDGs, particularly the relevance of public policy to the attainment of these goals

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to:
1. State the key issues, concepts, and developments in the field of transgender studies;
2. Distinguish the competing theoretical and empirical approaches to understanding and defining different gender identities;
3. Understand the notion of transgender in a cross-cultural perspective;
4. Recognize that other factors such as social class, sexuality, race/ethnicity and age cut across the issues pertinent to transgender studies;
5. Comment on the pros and cons of various understandings and definitions of transgender;
6. Theorize contemporary social issues in relation to transgender identities;
7. Critically engage with inequality and violence in society in relation to different modes and notions of gender, especially in relation to transgender people.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Acquire enhanced knowledge on gender studies theories and empirical findings across a wide range of academic fields;
2. Comprehend current affairs critically and analytically;
3. Be sensitive to the plurality and diversity of academic discussions and debates on DEI;
4. Explain the connection between academic research on different social minorities and practical intervention they informed and inspired
5. Encouraged to implement knowledge on gender studies in different fields and industries

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Acquire enhanced knowledge on DEI related theories and empirical findings across a wide range of academic fields;
2. Comprehend current affairs critically and analytically through the lens of DEI;
3. Be sensitive to the plurality and diversity of academic and communal practices of DEI;
4. Explain the connection between academic research on DEI and practical intervention they informed and inspired;
5. Encouraged to implement knowledge on DEI in different fields and industries.

By the end of the course students should be able to:
1. learn the on-site data-collection skills and techniques for fieldwork;
2. explore and develop his/her own research interests;
3. work in a team for an agreed goal/product and enhance the outcomes with the feedback received
4. present his/her own idea through verbal and written presentations
5. establish feasible plans to manage available resources for an agreed goal/product

Learning Outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students will be able to
1. complete a research project in the form of a thesis of not less than 8,000 words;
2. show knowledge of formulating research questions, doing a critical literature review, choosing relevant methodologies, making ethical decisions in relation to research, collecting, analyzing and interpreting data, making arguments, writing thesis with proper citation and making scholarly presentations;
3. critically review feminist methodologies in addressing the power relations between researchers and informants.

Students are expected to know and be able to:

1. understand the role of gender in China from past to present, and how gender was interwoven with social, cultural, economic and political forces;
2. analyse gender related elements that are reflected from sources, methodologies and discourses;
3. evaluate existing values and perceptions about gender issues in China and increase gender awareness.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to
1. further integrate theory and practice by applying theories to the issues arisen from real-life situations and subjecting theories to critical reflection through work experience;
2. demonstrate their knowledge of agencies working in the field of gender and sexuality, and understand their roles by embedding them in the historical, social, cultural and economic contexts of Hong Kong;
3. work and collaborate with others as a mature and critical social actor, and manage various challenges and difficulties with integrity, responsibility and commitment.

courses.course_syllabus:
Learning Activities:
• Students need to attend a pre-internship workshop;
• Internship starts from June to August during which students will be assigned to an agency in the field of gender and/or sexuality in Hong Kong, mostly likely a non-governmental organization, a university-affiliated unit or a charity group;
• Students will work for the agency for at least 8 hours per week over three months;
• Students need to submit a log to the supervisor every week;
• Students need to submit a final report of no less than 3,000 words two months after the completion of internship, reflecting on the experience of working as an intern, the connection between theory and practice, and the issues arisen from the internship.

