Upon successful completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Address issues surrounding the construction of gender/sexuality and the changing relations and sexual politics in the context of global modernities;
2. Emphasize the specificities of histories, regions, and localities in examining both changes and continuities in gender/sexuality representations as well as the lived realities of gender/sexuality experience;
3. Evaluate different legal and social policy responses to address the needs of people of diverse genders and sexualities, taking into account the cultural and social specificities in a globalizing world;
4. Understand how the needs of people of diverse genders and sexualities can be addressed in different social domains of life, such as employment and education.

1. Students will become familiar with social anthropological approaches to gender as a performance and also be able to compare and contrast the anthropological approach with other approaches;
2. Students will be able to determine what questions can be answered through gender performance theory and which cannot;
3. Students will be introduced to a variety of issues related to work in general - what it means to work, what issues individuals face in finding and keeping jobs, and why people do or do not succeed in the workplace;
4. Students will be encouraged to use the methods provided in class to analyze specific situations involving work and the effect of gender on success; and
5. Students will be able to approach gender in a variety of different ways and be sensitive to how different contexts require different approaches.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to do the followings:
1. understand an array of issues on gender and family in cross-cultural and local contexts, and analyze how family status and gender roles are being constructed;
2. critically take into consideration of various feminist theoretical approaches on marriage and family;
3. identify the transformation of gendered family ideals throughout the decades, and how do those ideals affect life cycles of both men and women;
4. integration of knowledge and practicality, students should become competent at relating and applying class learning to their daily observation of gender-family issues.

Upon successful completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Differentiate between women literature, feminist literature and feminine writing;
2. Recognize the gender representations in daily life and analyze its ideological content;
3. Understand the literature text introduced in the class and develop interests and self-learning initiative of other literature works;
4. Take into account the personal background of the author, the social historical context of the work of literature and the social response it receives and analyze it from the gender perspective;
5. Apply what is learnt on the topic and write dissertations on it.

